tbe causes acute meningitis, encephalitis, or meningoencephalitis with or without myelitis. severity of disease increases with age, with an excess of males and is highest in adults, of whom half develop encephalitis. it begins with fever (99%), fatigue, and general malaise (62%), headache and body pain (54%). in diphasic infections (eur), neurological symptoms appear 4–10 days after apparent recovery. fe disease is often severe with signs of encephalitis, focal epilepsy and flaccid paralysis of the shoulder girdle (cfr: 5–40%); eur is a milder disease, with death and severe sequelae less frequent than in fe. long-lasting or permanent neuropsychiatric sequelae are observed in 10–20% or more of infected patients. infections with the european and siberian subtypes are less severe (cfr: 1–3%).
